00:00:07.050 --> 00:00:12.550
PROFESSOR: OK, today's about
inverse functions, which is a

00:00:12.550 --> 00:00:16.020
new way to create one function
from another one.

00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:23.980
And the reason it's so important
is that we want to--

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:28.810
this, the logarithm, is going to
be the inverse function for

00:00:28.810 --> 00:00:30.270
e to the x.

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:34.090
We can't live without e to
the x on one side and the

00:00:34.090 --> 00:00:36.380
logarithm on the other side.

00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:39.680
So here's the idea of
inverse functions.

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:42.730
Well, here are the
letters we use.

00:00:42.730 --> 00:00:45.390
Usually y is f of x.

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:48.340
That's the standard letters.

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:54.390
Then, for the inverse, I'm going
to use f with a minus

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:56.940
one above the line.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:01:01.560
And notice though, it will
be x is f inverse of y.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:03.480
And let me show you
why that is.

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:06.310
Let's just remember what
a function is.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:11.180
So function like f
is, I take an x--

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:12.430
that's my input--

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:24.585
then the function acts on that
input and produces an output.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:37.400
At some level, this is what a
function is, a bunch of inputs

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.300
and the corresponding outputs.

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:42.890
OK, what's the inverse
function?

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:44.970
You can guess what's coming.

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:47.350
I'll reverse those.

00:01:47.350 --> 00:01:52.870
For the inverse function,
y will be the input.

00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:56.500
So y is now the input.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:01:59.710
What used to be the output
is now the input--

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:01.820
just turning them around.

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:07.400
Then the question is, what
x did it come from?

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:13.980
That x that y came from up here
is the x that it goes to

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:17.020
with the inverse function.

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:18.370
So you see the point?

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:21.230
X and y are just getting
reversed.

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:30.070
Let me do an example, because
that's letters, and we need a

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:31.580
first example.

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:35.010
y is x squared.

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:37.510
So that's my function f of x.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:41.140
f is this squaring function.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:47.090
If you give me x equals three,
the output is y equals nine.

00:02:47.090 --> 00:02:50.850
Now, what's the inverse
function?

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:54.770
The inverse function, I
want to find x from y.

00:02:54.770 --> 00:02:55.650
How do I do that?

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:57.270
I take the square root.

00:02:57.270 --> 00:03:00.590
So the inverse function
will be x is--

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:03.540
do you like to write square root
of y or do you like to

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:05.910
write y to the one half power?

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:07.300
Both good--

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:12.990
That's the inverse function of
the other, and, of course,

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:16.930
before we said, if x was
three y was nine.

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:22.680
And, now, if y is nine, then x
will come out to be the square

00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:26.090
root of nine, three.

00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:28.395
Oh, one small point--
well, not so small.

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:39.340
I was really staying there in
this example with x greater or

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:41.410
equal zero.

00:03:41.410 --> 00:03:46.440
I don't know want to allow
x equal minus three.

00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:48.170
Well, why not?

00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:51.130
Because if I allowed x equal
minus three as one of the

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:55.110
inputs, if I extended the
function x squared

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:57.840
to go for all x's.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:03.440
So if x equal minus three was
allowed input, then y would be

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:05.140
the same answer, nine.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:07.580
So I would be getting
nine from both

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:09.660
three and minus three.

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:14.520
And then, in the inverse,
I wouldn't know which

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:16.279
one to go back to.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:18.930
In the inverse, the input would
be nine, but should the

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:20.959
output be three or
minus three.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:26.900
So the point is, our functions
have to be--

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:31.360
one-to-one is a kind of nice
expression that gives you the

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:35.710
idea, one x for one y,
one y for one x.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:40.730
And that means that they're
graphs have to go steadily

00:04:40.730 --> 00:04:48.680
upwards or steadily downwards,
but not down and up the way y

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:52.930
equal x squared would if
I went over all x's.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:58.520
Let me do some more examples
before I come to the reason

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:04.750
for this lecture, which is the
exponential and the logarithm.

00:05:04.750 --> 00:05:08.650
And let's just look ahead to
what will come near the end of

00:05:08.650 --> 00:05:09.870
the lecture.

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:16.060
We know facts about the
exponential, e to the x, and

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:20.150
those facts, when I look at the
inverse function, give me

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:24.290
some different facts, important
facts still, about

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:25.130
the logarithm.

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:27.200
And here is the most
important one.

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:33.750
That the log of a product of two
numbers is the sum of the

00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:35.880
two logarithms, very
important fact.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:39.710
That simple but important
fact is what

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:41.970
made logarithms famous.

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:46.930
And it was the whole basis
for the slide rule.

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:48.870
Well, do you know what
a slide rule is?

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:50.340
Maybe you haven't
ever seen one?

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.140
Probably not.

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:56.600
Everybody had them, and then
suddenly nobody has any.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.690
But the point was, on a slide
rule you had a little stick,

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:00.585
another little stick--

00:06:00.585 --> 00:06:02.730
I used to drop the thing--

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:08.940
And you push out log y, and then
the second stick measures

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:14.310
out log capital Y, and then you
read off the answer of a

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:15.180
multiplication.

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:20.136
So you were able to multiply,
but kind of inaccurately.

00:06:20.136 --> 00:06:21.386
So--

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:27.110
But that doesn't mean that this

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:28.800
logarithm isn't still important.

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:31.500
It is, just not for
slide rules.

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:33.685
I promised two more examples.

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:38.820
Also this is a chance to
think about functions.

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:47.130
So what about the radius of
a circle r and the area a?

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:49.090
There is a function there.

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:56.260
The input is r, and the
area is pi r squared.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:07:05.230
So that's some function of
r, input r, output a.

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:07.850
Now, tell me the inverse
function.

00:07:07.850 --> 00:07:11.470
The inverse function, I'm
going to input a, and

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:13.120
I want to get r.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.310
So the input for the inverse
function, it's

00:07:16.310 --> 00:07:17.610
going to be like this.

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:20.430
I have to solve that
equation for r.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:26.140
How do I do that?

00:07:26.140 --> 00:07:27.390
I divide by pi.

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.820
That gives me r squared.

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:35.970
And then, just as there,
I take the square

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:37.910
root, and I have r.

00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:41.790
So that's the inverse
function of--

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:43.940
is that a function of r?

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:45.200
No way.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:46.570
The input is now a.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:49.840
This is a function of a.

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:53.720
Divide by pi, take the square
root, and you're back to r.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.260
Let me draw the pictures
that go with that.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:59.680
Because the graph of a function
and its inverse

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:02.430
function are really
quite neat.

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:05.260
So do you know what the
graph of a equals pi r

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:06.300
squared would look like?

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:11.190
Again, r is only going to be
positive, and, now, area's

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:12.710
only going to be positive.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:17.470
And the graph of pi r squared
is a parabola.

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:23.660
Say at r equal one, I
reach area equal--

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.480
What would be the area
if the radius is one?

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:32.799
Plug it in the formula,
the area is pi.

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:33.960
That's that point.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:35.445
And those are all the
other points.

00:08:35.445 --> 00:08:36.650
OK.

00:08:36.650 --> 00:08:43.309
So that's the graph, which
was nothing new.

00:08:43.309 --> 00:08:46.335
The new graph is the graph
of the inverse function.

00:08:46.335 --> 00:08:46.910
OK.

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:48.320
What's up?

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:59.590
This time the input is now
a, and the output is r.

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:02.900
If the area is 0,
the radius is 0.

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:05.320
If the area is pi--

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:07.750
Oh, look, I'm just going
to take this, and

00:09:07.750 --> 00:09:08.830
it's going to go here.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:15.300
If the area is pi, what's
the radius?

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:17.100
Well, put it in the formula.

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:20.030
If the area is pi, I have
pi over pi, one,

00:09:20.030 --> 00:09:21.090
square root's one.

00:09:21.090 --> 00:09:22.770
The radius is one, of
course it's one.

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:34.520
One there, so that's a point
on the graph of the inverse

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:39.050
function, of this square
root of a over pi.

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:42.850
And what's the rest
of the graph.

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:43.860
Does it look like that?

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:45.200
No way.

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:50.640
Everything is being flipped,
you could say, Or you could

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:56.860
say, a mirror image just
turned over here.

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:01.120
This thing, which started out
like this, is now a square

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:02.220
root function.

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:05.690
The square root function climbs
and comes around like

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:11.400
that like it's a parabola this
way, because that one was a

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:14.390
parabola that way.

00:10:14.390 --> 00:10:17.120
All right, let me go on
to a second example.

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:22.480
But that point that these graphs
just flip over the 45

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.940
degree line, it's because y and
x are getting switched.

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:28.346
Let me do the second example.

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:32.960
What about temperature?

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:41.170
We could measure temperature
in Fahrenheit, say f.

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:47.260
Or we can measure it in
centigrade or Celsius, say c.

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:49.850
And what's the function?

00:10:49.850 --> 00:10:53.950
If I take f, I want to know c.

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:59.340
The centigrade temperature
is some function of f.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.030
Let me at the same
time draw the

00:11:01.030 --> 00:11:03.470
picture so we can remember.

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:06.060
So this is now the
forward function.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:09.570
I'm creating f first, and then
I'm going to create f inverse.

00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:10.860
OK.

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:15.610
Do you remember the point
how they're connected?

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:18.000
Here is f.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.050
And we'll start with the
freezing point of water.

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:26.010
The freezing point of water is
32 Fahrenheit but is zero

00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:26.620
centigrade.

00:11:26.620 --> 00:11:30.410
That's why that system
got created.

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:35.220
So f equals 32, c equals zero.

00:11:35.220 --> 00:11:36.520
That's on the graph.

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:41.190
And then what's the
other key point?

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:48.140
The boiling point of water, so
say, that's one f is 212.

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:51.750
212 is the boiling point
of water in Fahrenheit.

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:56.150
And what's the boiling point
in Celsius, centigrade?

00:11:56.150 --> 00:11:57.050
100--

00:11:57.050 --> 00:11:58.860
I mean that system was--

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:03.440
I don't know where 32 and 212
came from, but 0 to 100 is

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:08.470
pretty sensible,
0 and then 100.

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:15.880
So that's the other point and
then, actually, the graph is

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.990
just straight line.

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:26.010
In fact, let's find
the formula.

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:28.950
What's the equation
for that line?

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:36.060
So I take f and I subtract 32,
so that gets me at the right

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:38.330
start, the right
freezing point.

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:42.810
And now I want to multiply by
the right slope to get up to

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:44.850
the right boiling point.

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:48.840
So when I go over 180,
I want to go up 100.

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:52.400
So it's 100 over 180.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:57.200
That 180 was the 32 to 212.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:02.040
So the ratio of 100 to 180
that's, well, five to nine

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:08.090
would be easier to write, so
let me write five to nine.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:12.680
Is that OK for the graph of
the original function?

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:16.960
This is my function
of f giving me c.

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:24.620
Ready for the inverse
function?

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:26.700
Can you do this with me?

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:29.950
c is now the input.

00:13:29.950 --> 00:13:32.600
